sections.name: etymology
sections.content: Considered derogatory until the 19th century; now the standard, neutral word. Origin uncertain; probably either from Old Polish kob (“pigpen”) or koba (“mare”); the suffix -ieta is found in some contemporaneous female names (Markieta, Elżbieta, Greta). Displaced niewiasta (now considered poetic) and żona (meaning narrowed down to "wife"). Or may derive from Proto-Slavic *kobь, from Proto-Indo-European *kob-. Akin to Belarusian кабе́та (kabjéta, “married woman”), (obsolete) Russian кобь (kobʹ), Old Norse happ (“good luck”), Old Irish cob (“victory”).
